R vs. C++

Why R ?

  • THE language for statistical data analysis
  • High flexibility
  • Many many extensions in packages
  • Interactive programming
  • Interpreted language
  • Slow

R vs. C++

Why R ?

  • THE language for statistical data analysis
  • High flexibility
  • Many many extensions in packages
  • Interactive programming
  • Interpreted language
  • Slow

Why C++

  • System programming; application development
  • Frequently used
    • Much available code
  • General purpose programming language
  • Compiled language
  • Fast

Why integration of R and C++ ?

1. Speed up R

2. Use of existing C++ code & libraries, e.g.

  • Armadillo, Eigen –> linear algebra
  • GNU scientific library
  • …

Challenges

  • C++ less well known among ecologists
  • Learn C++ syntax
  • Debug C++ code
  • Non-interactive programming

Typical bottlenecks in R

  • Loops (for-loops) that depend in previous iterations
    • E.g. MCMC algorithms
    • Dynamic simulation models
  • Problems which call functions many many times (e.g. recursive functions)
    • High overhead of functions calls in R vs. low overhead in C++
  • Lack of advanced data structures and algorithms in R
  • In C++ many important data structures in Standard Template Library (STL)

Linking R and C++ --- The old fashioned way

  1. Write C, C++ or FORTRAN code
  2. Compile shared object (.dll or .so) in command line terminal
  3. Load shared object into R with dyn.load()
  4. Call C++-function in R using .C() or .Call()

Complicated procedure

Painful way of passing data between R and C++

Did somebody do that already?

The experts opinion

Chambers (2008) Chapter 11: Interfaces I: Using C and Fortran

Since the core of R is in fact a program written in the C language, it's not surprising that the most direct interface to non-R software is for code written in C, or directly callable from C. All the same, including additional C code is a serious step, with some added dangers and often a substantial amount of programming and debugging required. You should have a good reason.

Linking R and C++ --- The modern way

  • Rcpp: R package by Dirk Eddelbuettel and Romain Francois
  • Easy to use – “seamless R and C++ integration”
  • Intuitive data types to pass data between R and C++
  • No worries about memory allocation

A minimal first example

#load library
library(Rcpp) 

# write C++ code
cppFunction(
   'int add(int x, int y, int z)
    {
      int sum = x + y + z;
      return sum;
    }'
)

# call function in R
add(1, 2, 3)

[1] 6

Separate source code files: C++ code

// C++ file  
// MyCPPcode.cpp
// This is a C++ comment

# include <Rcpp.h>
using namespace Rcpp;


// [[Rcpp::export]]
int add(int x, int y, int z)
{
   int sum = x + y + z;
   return sum;
}

Separate source code files: R code

library(Rcpp)
sourceCpp("Code/MyCPPCode.cpp")

add(1,2,3)

[1] 6

C++ Basics

  • Always explicit type declaration
  • Semi colon at the end of each statement
# R Code
number1 <- 0.5
number2 <- 5

// C++ Code
double number1 = 0.5;
int number2 = 5;

C++ Basics: Function declaration

  • Again explicit function value and argument types
  • Explicit return() statement
# R Code
addR <- function(a,b,c)
{
   a+b+c
}

// C++ Code
double add(double a, double b, double c)
{
   double sum = a+b+c;
   return sum;
}

For-loops in C++

  1. Starting value
  2. Condition
  3. Increment
int nmax = 1000;
int total = 0;

for (int i=0; i<nmax; ++i) //i=i+1
{
   total += i; //total = total + i
}

Vectors in Rcpp / C++

  • Datatype defined by Rcpp: NumericVector
    • numeric() in R
    • std::vector<double> from C++ STL
NumericVector xvec; //empty vector

int nmax = 100;
NumericVector xvec(nmax); //100 zeros

int Length = xvec.size();  //Get vector length

xvec[0];  //first value
xvec[nmax-1]; //last value

Remember: vectors in C++ are indexed from 0 – (length-1)

Rcpp sugar

  • Syntactic sugar for C++
  • Vectorized C++ functions that work like familiar R functions
  • Write (efficient!) C++ code that looks like R code (almost)

Cumsum in normal C++

// [[Rcpp::export]]
NumericVector cumsum_cpp(NumericVector x){

    // initialize an accumulator variable
    double acc = 0;

    // initialize the result vector
    NumericVector res(x.size());

    for(int i = 0; i < x.size(); ++i){
         acc += x[i];
         res[i] = acc;
    }
    return res;
}

Cumsum using R sugar

// [[Rcpp::export]]
NumericVector cumsum_sugar(NumericVector x){
   return cumsum(x);
}

Cumsum using R sugar

sourceCpp("Code/MyCPPcode.cpp")
library(microbenchmark)

x <- 1:999
microbenchmark(cumsum_cpp(x),cumsum_sugar(x),cumsum(x))

Available R sugar functions

  • Vectorized binary operators: +, -, *, /

  • Math functions, e. g. : abs(), ceil(), exp(), floor(), log(), sin(), sqrt(), …

  • Scalar summaries: mean(), min(), max(), sum(), sd()

  • Vector summaries: cumsum(), pmin(), and pmax().

  • Finding values: match(), which_max(), which_min()

  • Statistical functions: d/q/p/r for all standard distributions.

Checkout R sugar vignette in package Rcpp

Simulating Pi with Monte Carlo Method

  • Generate points in square: \( A = d^2 \)
  • Count proportion in circle: \( A = \frac{\pi}{4} * d^2 \)
  • Estimate of Pi:

\[ \pi \approx \frac{nPoints_{Circle}}{nPoints_{Total}} * 4 \]

Simulating Pi using R sugar

// [[Rcpp::export]]
double piSugar(const int N) {
    NumericVector x = runif(N);
    NumericVector y = runif(N);
    NumericVector d = sqrt(x*x + y*y);
    return 4.0 * sum(d < 1.0) / N;
}
  • Doesn't this look familiar?
piSugar(1e5)

[1] 3.14528

Finally some ecological modelling

  • Stochastic population dynamics
    • \( N(t+1) = N(t) + B - D \)
    • Constant per-capita probability of birth per time step: b
    • Density dependence: Per-capita probability of death increases with abundance: d*N(t)

Hints for R-function

nB <- rbinom(n=1,size=N[t-1],prob=b_rate)

  • Probabilities of death and birth <= 1

Demo #2: Population growth

Hints for C++

  • R sugar function rbinom
    • No named arguments
    • rbinom(1,N[t-1],b_rate)
    • Minimum of two number in C++: std::min(a,b)
    • Type conversion from rbinom to int
int nBirth = as<int>(rbinom(1,N[t-1],b_rate))
  • as<Type>(x) –> general function for type conversion from R to C++ types
  • wrap(x) –> opposite way: conversion from C++ to R

Rcpp in existing packages

  • Rcpp: most widely used language extension for R
  • 379 packages on CRAN (out of ca. 7,000) and 57 on BioConductor use Rcpp (May 2015)

A few examples:

  • High performance linear algebra
    • RcppEigen
    • RcppArmadillo (Matlab like syntax)
  • General scientific computing
    • RcppGSL (GNU Scientific library)
  • Parallel programming: RcppParallel

Using Rcpp in your own R packages

Benefits of R package vs. single C++ code file

  • Code availability for users without C++ development tools (e.g. Rtools for Windows)
  • Multiple source files and their dependencies are handled automatically by the R package build system.
  • Additional infrastructure for testing, documentation, and consistency.

Package development support

  • In Rcpp: Rcpp.package.skeleton()
  • RStudio support in package development
